Latvia
April 3rd 2020
The SPKC launches a public awareness measure ...
    Stay at home , if possible, work remotely and refrain from visiting public places at all or only when absolutely necessary;
    Wash your hands with soap and do it often, thoroughly, for at least 20 seconds. It is especially important to wash your hands when returning home after visiting public places, after sneezing and coughing, after contact with patients or their surroundings, after visiting the toilet, before eating and in other cases;
    a two meters Always keep distance of from other people or social distance when you still have to go outside the home.

Latvia
March 30th 2020
Public catering is allowed to occur so long as they obey the following rules:

    -two meters distance between tables;
    -no more than two visitors may be at the same table, except for members of the same family;
    -in the cash register and service area, a distance of two meters from the visitor standing in front of the queue with delimiting signs;
    -the maximum permissible number of visitors in the catering hall - one visitor per at least 4 m2 of the total area of ​​the catering hall;
    -possibility to buy food to take away.
    -an invitation must be placed at the entrance for the visitor not to visit the public catering place if he or she has shown signs of a respiratory infection;
    -inform visitors about the maximum number of persons that can be in the catering premises at the same time;
    -to be socially responsible and to observe a distance of 2 meters from the surrounding visitors when there are clearly visible signs placed in places visible to visitors (at least at the cash desk and at the entrance to the place of provision of catering services);
    -a statement in Latvian must be played every 15 minutes, urging you not to linger in public catering premises and to follow the instructions regarding observance of the distance. The catering provider may additionally choose other foreign languages ​​to play the announcement.

Starting November 27, 2020, the Latvian government introduces additional restrictive measures:
-museums and other cultural venues will not open;
-amateur sports can only take place outdoors;
-no private events may take place except funerals.

City public transportation fill must not exceed 50% capacity, whereas stores and other indoor service locations may not exceed 20% of the maximum possible number of people in-store at the same time. 

These additional rules were introduced in 12 municipalities: Daugavpils, Baldone, Krāslava, Salacgrīva, Aknīste, Varakļāni, Mārupe, Mālpils, Smiltene, Garkalne, Limbaži and Salaspils.

On December 1, 2020, the Latvian government decided on stricter and more precise safety measures are being introduced until 11 January 2021:
- principle 2 + 2 shall be observed by everyone in Latvia - a distance of two meters must be observed and meetings must be limited to two people;
-operation of all cultural sites, exhibitions, fairs, including Christmas markets, shall be prohibited. Libraries are allowed on site to loan out books and museums are still available to visitors;
-at funerals and christening ceremonies held in urgent cases, no more than 10 people (excluding those directly involved, such as the clergy) may gather outdoors, from no more than two households, 
-private events shall be prohibited, except than within a single household. It is allowed to visit people who live alone and need care;
-no more than 20% of the maximum number of people may be present at the same time in places of religious activity;
-organized meetings, pickets, and marches are still allowed, but a maximum of 25 people is allowed to attend.

